      <h5>The problem</h5>
      <h3 class="section-title">Cutting through the noise</h3>
      <p class="p--large">Bright Funds is a for-profit, for-good enterprise product that companies use to run their giving and volunteering benefits. What we were seeing from our data and hearing from the people running giving and volunteering programs was that people love the benefits we offer, but they were being under used.</p>
      <p class="p--large">People are busy at work (that’s a good thing!). But as a result, soft benefits like having your donations matched were slipping through the cracks. We would see an uptick during certain seasons (IE holiday giving), but see engagement slip during other parts of the year.</p>

      <h3>The challenge</h3>
      <p>Develop a process to discover and quickly test projects that boost awareness of Bright Funds within companies and increase engagement once an employee begins using the product.</p>

      <h3>My role</h3>
      <p>An engineer and I took up the challenge to understand why benefits like this were being under-used and to iterate through possible features that could boost awareness and engagement.</p>
      <p>My role included</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Collecting and ranking engagement ideas</li>
        <li>Project planning and scope definition</li>
        <li>Experience design</li>
        <li>UI design</li>
      </ul>

    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="grid">
    <div class="case-study__content-wrapper--md grid--centered-sm" data-aos="fade-up">
      <h5>Shaping the idea</h5>
      <h3>Researching the problem</h3>
      <p>To get started, I held conversations with employees, looked at usage data, and read through customer support conversations to understand what was holding people back from using their giving and volunteer benefits - especially because most people are already doing this outside of work.</p>

      <h3>Early insights</h3>
      <p>From this research, we identified several key insights:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Overall awareness within companies can be low.</strong><br>People are busy with their work and daily lives. Often, giving benefits are explained as part of an employee’s onboarding, but people are already way too overloaded in those first few weeks. Giving and matching doesn’t stick.</li>
        <li><strong>People often only log in once per year.</strong><br>Many companies run a service week or end of year giving campaign where they drum up awareness. After that many people don’t come back.</li>
        <li><strong>People don’t know everything they can do.</strong><br>For example, we get people reaching out with questions like: “I made a donation to a friend’s race, can that be matched?”. As a result, people don't take full advantage of the product.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>These problems result in people leaving matching on the table that they could have used or not taking advantage of their volunteer benefits.</p>

      <h3>From problem to opportunity</h3>
      <p>I repositioned these problems into opportunities.</p>
      <ol>
        <li>How might we make people within companies aware of the benefits available to them?</li>
        <li>How might boost engagement of company giving and volunteering benefits throughout the year?</li>
        <li>How might help people take full advantage of all the giving and volunteering benefits they have?</li>
      </ol>

      <p>Next, we began thinking through possible solutions for these opportunities.</p>

      <h3>Gathering ideas</h3>
      <p>First, I needed to gather ideas for how we might act on these opportunities. How we might increase awareness, increase retention, and help people take full advantage of the benefits available to them. To do so, I decided to collect ideas from throughout the company.</p>
      <p>Valuable insights live within various teams. For example, customer support might know which features come up frequently in support conversations and what users aren't quite understanding. Sales might know how companies are looking to increase awareness within their company.</p>
      <p>To gather ideas from around the company, I developed a pitch document. When someone had an idea they’d like to share, they wrote out what the idea was, why they think it would be effective, and how it could be measured. This document was then shared in a slack channel.</p>
      <p>The purpose behind writing out the idea was to encourage concrete thinking. This way, once the team was ready to review which projects to take on, we had a good idea of the work that would be required to make something happen and what success looks like.</p>

      <h3>Choosing projects</h3>
      <p>A group from the product team would meet every few weeks and discuss ideas that had been submitted.</p>
      <p>There’s not one magic method to decide on which projects to take on. In this case, we made decisions based on what we believed would have high impact, what would be within our desired effort to build (we wanted to keep each project small, around 2-4 weeks work), and whether we’ve heard specific requests from clients.</p>
    </div>
