      <h3>Fundraising</h3>
      <p>Focus: <span class="definition-badge">Awareness</span>, <span class="definition-badge">Frequency of usage</span></p>
      <p>We knew that the awareness of giving and matching programs could be pretty low within companies. Soft benefits like these aren’t critical to someone’s work and they don’t earn the same attention as benefits like insurance and retirement savings.</p>
      <p>We wanted to increase awareness. At the same time, we were wary of a traditional awareness campaign, because each company handled their internal comms differently. Company A might use email, company B Slack, company C an internally built tool. On top of that, each company would likely want to control what they say, how they say it, and when. At the same time, we didn’t want to invest effort in a project that would result in messages silently landing in inboxes.</p>
      <p>However, we did know that fundraising is a key driver for giving. Fundraising for a birthday, for a race, or for a personal reason is extremely popular (IE Facebook fundraisers, charity: water, GoFundMe). Fundraisers are also inherently social. We figured this could be a natural growth mechanism within companies.</p>
      <p>Our hunch was that we could encourage people to fundraise on Bright Funds with the knowledge that donations would be matched (therefore doubling the amount raised). This could be a trojan horse. The coworkers that supported the fundraiser would then be introduced to Bright Funds and could learn about the other benefits available to them.</p>
      <p>At the time, people could set up Funds - think mutual funds for giving. We decided to adapt this concept to allow adding a goal and a deadline to test fundraisers.</p>

    </div>

